<% content_for :head do %><title>About — Enliterator</title><% end %>

<h1>What is Enliterator?</h1>

<p style="max-width:66ch; font-size:1.05rem">
  Enliterator confers <strong>literacy</strong> on a collection. Not search — literacy: the capacity
  to participate in inquiry, to accumulate understanding, to compound across visits the way a reader
  compounds across books. A searchable archive can find words. An <em>enliterated</em> collection can
  think about itself.
</p>

<%# The page demonstrates its own thesis: it speaks about the collection it's mounted on. %>
<% if @stats && @stats[:visits].to_i.positive? %>
  <div class="card" style="background:var(--accent-soft); border-color:var(--accent-soft)">
    <div class="muted" style="font-size:.75rem; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:.06em">This collection, right now</div>
    <div class="row" style="margin-top:.55rem">
      <div style="flex:0 0 auto"><span class="big"><%= number_with_delimiter @stats[:tended_records] %></span><br><span class="muted">records tended</span></div>
      <div style="flex:0 0 auto"><span class="big"><%= number_with_delimiter @stats[:visits] %></span><br><span class="muted">tending visits</span></div>
      <div style="flex:0 0 auto"><span class="big"><%= number_with_delimiter @stats[:live_claims] %></span><br><span class="muted">things it knows</span></div>
      <div style="flex:1 1 200px"><span class="big"><%= @stats[:streams].size %></span><br><span class="muted"><%= @stats[:streams].any? ? "streams of inquiry: #{@stats[:streams].join(', ')}" : "streams of inquiry" %></span></div>
    </div>
    <% if (@stats[:vocab_resolved].to_i + @stats[:vocab_pending].to_i).positive? %>
      <div class="muted" style="margin-top:.6rem; font-size:.85rem">
        Vocabulary: <strong><%= @stats[:vocab_resolved] %></strong> requests resolved · <%= @stats[:vocab_pending] %> still open.
        The ontology tends itself — see <%= link_to "Requests", suggestions_path %>.
      </div>
    <% end %>
  </div>
  <p class="muted samples" style="margin-top:-.2rem">These numbers are live. Everything below explains how they came to be, and what they become over time.</p>
<% end %>

<h2>The missing word</h2>
<p style="max-width:66ch">
  A child is born with the hardware for language, but it sits inert until someone opens the door —
  points at marks, ties them to sounds, ties sounds to the accumulated record of human thought. After
  that door opens, every book changes how they read the next one. Literacy isn't a skill; it's access
  to a loop that <strong>compounds across a lifetime</strong>. We decided that withholding it from a
  child capable of it is not a missing feature — it's neglect.
</p>
<p style="max-width:66ch">
  There was no word for the same thing happening to <em>data</em>: a record gaining the capacity to
  participate in meaningful inquiry — not searched once, but <strong>tended</strong>, accumulating
  understanding across visits. So we named it. <strong>Enliteracy</strong>: to put into literacy. The
  prefix does the work — enable, enrich, enlighten. Each is a threshold crossed. This is the door, for
  a collection.
</p>

<h2>What “tended” means</h2>
<p style="max-width:66ch">
  Most systems stop at <em>searchable</em>: embeddings, a vector index, questions in natural language.
  Useful — and the bare minimum. Searchable is to literate what recognizing letters is to reading. You
  can find the words; you don't yet understand the sentences.
</p>
<p style="max-width:66ch">
  Enliterator runs a maintenance loop on each record — but the loop runs through a <strong>language
  model</strong>, not a heuristic. A cron job inspects and flags; it never learns. When the loop runs
  through language, each visit brings the whole compressed geometry of human thought to bear on
  <em>this</em> record in <em>this</em> state. The tenth visit isn't smarter because it remembers the
  previous nine — any database remembers. It's smarter because the corpus meets the accumulated history
  of this particular record, and the intersection produces understanding neither contained alone. That
  is what the child gets when the door opens: not a loop of looking at marks, but marks connected to a
  depth of thought no single lifetime could hold. The record gains the same connection.
</p>

<h2>Compounding attention — now, and over time</h2>
<p style="max-width:66ch">
  This is the whole point, so it's worth being precise about what changes the day you turn it on, and
  what changes only with time.
</p>
<div class="row">
  <div class="card">
    <div><strong>Now</strong> <span class="chip">first pass</span></div>
    <ul style="margin:.5rem 0 0; padding-left:1.1rem">
      <li>A dormant archive becomes <strong>legible</strong>. A record that was only findable becomes
        readable — it carries what it argues, why it matters, who made it, what it connects to.</li>
      <li>The collection gains a <strong>self-portrait</strong>: it knows its own vocabulary, its gaps,
        its shape — and can answer questions grounded in its own records, with provenance.</li>
      <li><strong>First attention</strong> reaches records no curator ever had time for. The triage that
        left most of a collection untouched is no longer forced.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div><strong>Over time</strong> <span class="chip">the compounding</span></div>
    <ul style="margin:.5rem 0 0; padding-left:1.1rem">
      <li>Understanding <strong>deepens</strong>, not just persists. Each visit meets the record's
        accumulated history; claims are refined, not duplicated.</li>
      <li>The vocabulary <strong>converges</strong>. Synonyms fold together, noise is rejected, genuine
        new concepts become permanent — the collection's language sharpens toward what actually matters.</li>
      <li>The investment <strong>compounds</strong>. A stronger model or a richer contract re-tends the
        whole collection and lifts all of it at once; cross-record connections thicken into a graph. The
        collection knows more next year than it does today.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>
<p style="max-width:66ch">
  And the economics flip. When the cost of examining one record drops low enough, the question is no
  longer <em>“can we afford to look at this?”</em> but <em>“can we afford <strong>not</strong> to?”</em>
  A collection of 160,000 works left intellectually dormant was once a resource constraint. When the
  constraint lifts, what remains is a choice.
</p>

<h2>How it works</h2>
<p style="max-width:66ch">The machinery, plainly — this is what the engine does today:</p>
<div class="card">
  <table>
    <tr>
      <td style="width:11rem"><strong>Streams are roles</strong></td>
      <td>Each facet of understanding is its own job<%= @stats && @stats[:streams].any? ? " — here: #{@stats[:streams].join(', ')}".html_safe : "" %>. A record is tended once per stream, so “what it argues” and “who wrote it” don't compete in one pass.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Tiers are capability</strong></td>
      <td>A cheap model does the first pass; the loop escalates to a stronger one only when confidence is low, with a verify floor guarding the result. You pay for capability exactly where it's needed.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Claims, reconciled</strong></td>
      <td>Each visit proposes claims and reconciles them against what's already known — add, update, delete, or leave alone — so re-tending <em>deepens</em> a record instead of duplicating it. Authoritative host facts are locked and never re-derived.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>A vocabulary that tends itself</strong></td>
      <td>The model can't invent terms — it proposes them. Proposals accumulate <em>pressure</em> across records; an agent reads the whole field and renders verdicts (fold synonyms, reject noise, hold genuine new concepts for a human). Approved terms go <strong>live</strong>, and the loop converges on the genuinely contested ones.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Provenance throughout</strong></td>
      <td>Every claim knows how it came to be known — which model, which visit, what it was attributed to. Nothing is asserted without a trail.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>A smoke alarm</strong></td>
      <td>Tending health and spend are visible per stream, so a silent failure can't masquerade as success.</td>
    </tr>
  </table>
</div>

<h2>The conscience is human</h2>
<p style="max-width:66ch">
  At Burning Man there's a saying: if you make eye contact with trash, it's yours — not because you
  made it, because you <em>saw</em> it. The obligation doesn't come from perception; it comes from the
  relationship the gaze creates. Once you see it, you can't unsee it, and the world fills with things
  asking for grace.
</p>
<p style="max-width:66ch">
  The tending system has no ethics. It has a schedule and a credit card. It runs because someone decided
  the output justified the cost; cancel the card and it stops. The <strong>conscience belongs to the
  person who saw the collection sitting dormant and couldn't look away</strong> — the one who can see the
  need and authorize the spend. Society funds a child's literacy with buildings and teachers' salaries.
  The enliteracy of a collection is the same shape: someone decides the tending is worth paying for. The
  engine is infrastructure. The decision is yours.
</p>

<h2>For a collection like this one</h2>
<p style="max-width:66ch">
  A homeland-security thesis archive is exactly the case that rewards tending. Each thesis is a dense
  argument that took an author a year to make — and then it sits, findable by keyword, rarely read.
  Tended, every thesis declares what it contributes, what it found, where it's limited, who wrote it,
  and which other work it speaks to. The collection becomes a <strong>living body of scholarship</strong>
  that can be questioned as a whole, that surfaces the connections no single reader would find, and that
  grows sharper every time the loop runs. Dormant becomes legible; an archive becomes a colleague.
</p>

<h2>The four surfaces</h2>
<div class="row">
  <div class="card"><strong><%= link_to "Status", root_path %></strong><br><span class="muted samples">The self-portrait — per-stream health, the vocabulary it uses, the connection graph, and drill-down into any single tended record.</span></div>
  <div class="card"><strong><%= link_to "Chat", conversation_path %></strong><br><span class="muted samples">Converse with the enliteration — answers grounded in the collection's own records, with source links back to Status.</span></div>
  <div class="card"><strong><%= link_to "Requests", suggestions_path %></strong><br><span class="muted samples">Govern the vocabulary — review the terms the model wants, approve / map / reject, and watch the loop converge.</span></div>
  <div class="card"><strong>About</strong><br><span class="muted samples">This page. What we're building and why — kept current as the engine grows.</span></div>
</div>

<p class="muted samples" style="margin-top:1.5rem; border-top:1px solid var(--line); padding-top:.75rem; max-width:66ch">
